Biological psychology, also known as biopsychology, is a branch of psychology that focuses on the study of the biological basis of behavior and mental processes. It explores the relationship between the brain, nervous system, and behavior, examining how biological factors influence cognitive processes, emotions, and behavior.

Biological psychology investigates various aspects, including:

1. Neuroanatomy and neurophysiology
2. Brain development and plasticity
3. Genetics and epigenetics
4. Hormones and neurotransmitters
5. Sensory and motor systems
6. Sleep and wakefulness
7. Emotions and motivation
8. Learning and memory
9. Psychopharmacology

Biological psychologists use techniques like functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), electroencephalography (EEG), and behavioral experiments to understand the biological mechanisms underlying human behavior and mental processes.

This field has led to significant advances in our understanding of various psychological and neurological conditions, such as anxiety disorders, depression, Alzheimer's disease, and Parkinson's disease.

The Uttar Pradesh Subordinate Services Selection Commission (UPSSSC) recently announced the Homeopathic Pharmacist vacancy for 2024, requiring candidates to have passed the Preliminary Eligibility Test (PET) in 2023. This requirement poses significant challenges for several reasons:
Specific DHP Course: The Diploma in Homeopathic Pharmacy (DHP) course, recently introduced, has a limited number of students. The PET exam is typically used for sorting a large number of applicants, but in this case, the student pool is small, rendering the PET requirement unnecessary.
Logistical Challenges: Many candidates, especially girls, faced difficulties in attending the 2023 PET due to distant exam centers and other logistical issues. Some candidates were unable to appear due to health reasons.
Annual PET and Vacancy Misalignment: The PET exam is conducted annually, yet corresponding vacancies are not guaranteed each year. This misalignment has led to frustration among candidates who took the PET in previous years when no relevant vacancies were announced.
Impact on Candidates: The sudden announcement of the 2024 vacancy with a 2023 PET requirement has disadvantaged many dedicated students who have been preparing for years. This situation is akin to conducting the NEET exam annually without ensuring that medical college seats are available each year.

What about KVS 2022 recruitment exam? That scam dissolved into thin air.    

1. CBT exam questions got changed when the answer key was released. One question which was there in general awareness section, just disappeared. 
2. Online solvers were caught in many centers.  
3. Exams were conducted by an agency which was blacklisted before. 
4.Toppers were from some selected centers in NorthEast, where people from even Haryana, Rajasthan went to appear.  
5. Interview marks of all candidates not released even after 8 months of Selection List. 

6. The above 5 points are all just the tip of the iceberg. There are unconfirmed reports of seats being booked even before the CBT, and also, people who couldn't even write an equation properly, were selected in interview. 

Sadly the scale of KVS exam is much smaller than NEET exam. Also, some candidates who scored good marks and cleared the sky-high cutoff, were rejected in the interview which went very well, and received verbal appreciation from the interviewers. These candidates were too late to go the Judiciary.

Dear Dhruv,

We hope this message finds you well. We are N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed candidates, and we are writing on behalf of the N.I.O.S D.El.Ed teachers from across the country. We are facing a critical issue that has affected approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers who were employed in government and private primary schools across India. Your platform has the power to bring our plight to the forefront, and we earnestly request your support in ventilating our voice throughout India.

Background Information:

With due respect, we would like to inform you that we are N.I.O.S D.El.Ed Teachers from across the country. According to the RTE-2009, every child has the fundamental right to receive primary education from a trained teacher. To ensure the fundamental rights of children, the Indian government passed a bill in both houses of Parliament with consensus in 2017. Through this, government, government-aided, and private school teachers who were untrained as of the 2010 NCTE notification were given the opportunity to complete the D.El.Ed course through NIOS. Thereafter, the Ministry of Human Resource Development (MHRD) issued a letter to all the Secretaries of States and Union Territories, directing that all teachers in government schools must possess minimum qualifications as mandated under the Right to Education Act, 2009, and a last chance was given to all teachers to acquire the same by March 31, 2019.

In 2017, the Modi government urged us to enroll in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) conducted by N.I.O.S. Approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers, who were already employed in government and private primary schools across the country, enrolled. Subsequently, NCTE issued a recognition order to be published in the Gazette, thereby conducting the D.El.Ed program through the Open and Distance Learning (ODL) mode by NIOS, which reduced the duration of the program from 2 years to 18 months. Education Minister Prakash Javadekar (at that time) and our PM Narendra Damodardas Modi emphasized our enrollment in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) through the National Institute of Open Schooling (NIOS). Normally, the program of the course is 2 years (18 months of theory and 6 months of internship), but our course was completed within 2 sessions (18 months) as we were already employed and did not require an internship. NIOS Board conducted all the exams for this course. It was promoted by Prime Minister Narendra Modi.

Current Situation:

According to the rules, this new plan of NCTE and the Modi government had to be published in the Gazette, but NCTE did not comply. As a result, in 2023, after 7 years, the Honourable Supreme Court announced that our degree is not valid for new recruitment. We cannot apply for any new recruitment in government schools and will not be able to do so in the future due to the negligence of NCTE and the false guarantee by Modi. Due to this mistake by Narendra Modi, today, 14 lakh families are suffering, with no solution in sight.

Our Request:

We, the 14 lakh affected teachers, humbly request your support to highlight our situation on your channel. Your influence and reach can help us gain the attention of the authorities and the public, potentially leading to a resolution of our predicament. We believe that with your help, we can bring our issue to the forefront and seek justice for the countless teachers who have dedicated their lives to educating the children of our country.

Thank you for your time and consideration. We sincerely hope that you will be able to support us in this crucial matter.

Warm regards,

N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed SONGAMI MONCHO 
+918777320749 (Whatsapp)

Dear Dhruv,

We hope this message finds you well. We are N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed candidates, and we are writing on behalf of the N.I.O.S D.El.Ed teachers from across the country. We are facing a critical issue that has affected approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers who were employed in government and private primary schools across India. Your platform has the power to bring our plight to the forefront, and we earnestly request your support in ventilating our voice throughout India.

Background Information:

With due respect, we would like to inform you that we are N.I.O.S D.El.Ed Teachers from across the country. According to the RTE-2009, every child has the fundamental right to receive primary education from a trained teacher. To ensure the fundamental rights of children, the Indian government passed a bill in both houses of Parliament with consensus in 2017. Through this, government, government-aided, and private school teachers who were untrained as of the 2010 NCTE notification were given the opportunity to complete the D.El.Ed course through NIOS. Thereafter, the Ministry of Human Resource Development (MHRD) issued a letter to all the Secretaries of States and Union Territories, directing that all teachers in government schools must possess minimum qualifications as mandated under the Right to Education Act, 2009, and a last chance was given to all teachers to acquire the same by March 31, 2019.

Dear Dhruv,

We hope this message finds you well. We are N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed candidates, and we are writing on behalf of the N.I.O.S D.El.Ed teachers from across the country. We are facing a critical issue that has affected approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers who were employed in government and private primary schools across India. Your platform has the power to bring our plight to the forefront, and we earnestly request your support in ventilating our voice throughout India.

Background Information:

With due respect, we would like to inform you that we are N.I.O.S D.El.Ed Teachers from across the country. According to the RTE-2009, every child has the fundamental right to receive primary education from a trained teacher. To ensure the fundamental rights of children, the Indian government passed a bill in both houses of Parliament with consensus in 2017. Through this, government, government-aided, and private school teachers who were untrained as of the 2010 NCTE notification were given the opportunity to complete the D.El.Ed course through NIOS. Thereafter, the Ministry of Human Resource Development (MHRD) issued a letter to all the Secretaries of States and Union Territories, directing that all teachers in government schools must possess minimum qualifications as mandated under the Right to Education Act, 2009, and a last chance was given to all teachers to acquire the same by March 31, 2019.

In 2017, the Modi government urged us to enroll in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) conducted by N.I.O.S. Approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers, who were already employed in government and private primary schools across the country, enrolled. Subsequently, NCTE issued a recognition order to be published in the Gazette, thereby conducting the D.El.Ed program through the Open and Distance Learning (ODL) mode by NIOS, which reduced the duration of the program from 2 years to 18 months. Education Minister Prakash Javadekar (at that time) and our PM Narendra Damodardas Modi emphasized our enrollment in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) through the National Institute of Open Schooling (NIOS). Normally, the program of the course is 2 years (18 months of theory and 6 months of internship), but our course was completed within 2 sessions (18 months) as we were already employed and did not require an internship. NIOS Board conducted all the exams for this course. It was promoted by Prime Minister Narendra Modi.

Current Situation:

According to the rules, this new plan of NCTE and the Modi government had to be published in the Gazette, but NCTE did not comply. As a result, in 2023, after 7 years, the Honourable Supreme Court announced that our degree is not valid for new recruitment. We cannot apply for any new recruitment in government schools and will not be able to do so in the future due to the negligence of NCTE and the false guarantee by Modi. Due to this mistake by Narendra Modi, today, 14 lakh families are suffering, with no solution in sight.

Our Request:

We, the 14 lakh affected teachers, humbly request your support to highlight our situation on your channel. Your influence and reach can help us gain the attention of the authorities and the public, potentially leading to a resolution of our predicament. We believe that with your help, we can bring our issue to the forefront and seek justice for the countless teachers who have dedicated their lives to educating the children of our country.

Thank you for your time and consideration. We sincerely hope that you will be able to support us in this crucial matter.

Warm regards,

N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed SONGAMI MONCHO

Dear Dhruv,

We hope this message finds you well. We are N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed candidates, and we are writing on behalf of the N.I.O.S D.El.Ed teachers from across the country. We are facing a critical issue that has affected approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers who were employed in government and private primary schools across India. Your platform has the power to bring our plight to the forefront, and we earnestly request your support in ventilating our voice throughout India.

Background Information:

With due respect, we would like to inform you that we are N.I.O.S D.El.Ed Teachers from across the country. According to the RTE-2009, every child has the fundamental right to receive primary education from a trained teacher. To ensure the fundamental rights of children, the Indian government passed a bill in both houses of Parliament with consensus in 2017. Through this, government, government-aided, and private school teachers who were untrained as of the 2010 NCTE notification were given the opportunity to complete the D.El.Ed course through NIOS. Thereafter, the Ministry of Human Resource Development (MHRD) issued a letter to all the Secretaries of States and Union Territories, directing that all teachers in government schools must possess minimum qualifications as mandated under the Right to Education Act, 2009, and a last chance was given to all teachers to acquire the same by March 31, 2019.

In 2017, the Modi government urged us to enroll in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) conducted by N.I.O.S. Approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers, who were already employed in government and private primary schools across the country, enrolled. Subsequently, NCTE issued a recognition order to be published in the Gazette, thereby conducting the D.El.Ed program through the Open and Distance Learning (ODL) mode by NIOS, which reduced the duration of the program from 2 years to 18 months. Education Minister Prakash Javadekar (at that time) and our PM Narendra Damodardas Modi emphasized our enrollment in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) through the National Institute of Open Schooling (NIOS). Normally, the program of the course is 2 years (18 months of theory and 6 months of internship), but our course was completed within 2 sessions (18 months) as we were already employed and did not require an internship. NIOS Board conducted all the exams for this course. It was promoted by Prime Minister Narendra Modi.

Current Situation:

According to the rules, this new plan of NCTE and the Modi government had to be published in the Gazette, but NCTE did not comply. As a result, in 2023, after 7 years, the Honourable Supreme Court announced that our degree is not valid for new recruitment. We cannot apply for any new recruitment in government schools and will not be able to do so in the future due to the negligence of NCTE and the false guarantee by Modi. Due to this mistake by Narendra Modi, today, 14 lakh families are suffering, with no solution in sight.

Our Request:

We, the 14 lakh affected teachers, humbly request your support to highlight our situation on your channel. Your influence and reach can help us gain the attention of the authorities and the public, potentially leading to a resolution of our predicament. We believe that with your help, we can bring our issue to the forefront and seek justice for the countless teachers who have dedicated their lives to educating the children of our country.

Thank you for your time and consideration. We sincerely hope that you will be able to support us in this crucial matter.

Warm regards,

N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed. session 2017-2019

Dear Dhruv,

We hope this message finds you well. We are N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed candidates, and we are writing on behalf of the N.I.O.S D.El.Ed teachers from across the country. We are facing a critical issue that has affected approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers who were employed in government and private primary schools across India. Your platform has the power to bring our plight to the forefront, and we earnestly request your support in ventilating our voice throughout India.

Background Information:

With due respect, we would like to inform you that we are N.I.O.S D.El.Ed Teachers from across the country. According to the RTE-2009, every child has the fundamental right to receive primary education from a trained teacher. To ensure the fundamental rights of children, the Indian government passed a bill in both houses of Parliament with consensus in 2017. Through this, government, government-aided, and private school teachers who were untrained as of the 2010 NCTE notification were given the opportunity to complete the D.El.Ed course through NIOS. Thereafter, the Ministry of Human Resource Development (MHRD) issued a letter to all the Secretaries of States and Union Territories, directing that all teachers in government schools must possess minimum qualifications as mandated under the Right to Education Act, 2009, and a last chance was given to all teachers to acquire the same by March 31, 2019.

In 2017, the Modi government urged us to enroll in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) conducted by N.I.O.S. Approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers, who were already employed in government and private primary schools across the country, enrolled. Subsequently, NCTE issued a recognition order to be published in the Gazette, thereby conducting the D.El.Ed program through the Open and Distance Learning (ODL) mode by NIOS, which reduced the duration of the program from 2 years to 18 months. Education Minister Prakash Javadekar (at that time) and our PM Narendra Damodardas Modi emphasized our enrollment in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) through the National Institute of Open Schooling (NIOS). Normally, the program of the course is 2 years (18 months of theory and 6 months of internship), but our course was completed within 2 sessions (18 months) as we were already employed and did not require an internship. NIOS Board conducted all the exams for this course. It was promoted by Prime Minister Narendra Modi.

Current Situation:

According to the rules, this new plan of NCTE and the Modi government had to be published in the Gazette, but NCTE did not comply. As a result, in 2023, after 7 years, the Honourable Supreme Court announced that our degree is not valid for new recruitment. We cannot apply for any new recruitment in government schools and will not be able to do so in the future due to the negligence of NCTE and the false guarantee by Modi. Due to this mistake by Narendra Modi, today, 14 lakh families are suffering, with no solution in sight.

Our Request:

We, the 14 lakh affected teachers, humbly request your support to highlight our situation on your channel. Your influence and reach can help us gain the attention of the authorities and the public, potentially leading to a resolution of our predicament. We believe that with your help, we can bring our issue to the forefront and seek justice for the countless teachers who have dedicated their lives to educating the children of our country.

Thank you for your time and consideration. We sincerely hope that you will be able to support us in this crucial matter.

Warm regards,

N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed. session 2017-2019

Dear Dhruv,

We hope this message finds you well. We are N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed candidates, and we are writing on behalf of the N.I.O.S D.El.Ed teachers from across the country. We are facing a critical issue that has affected approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers who were employed in government and private primary schools across India. Your platform has the power to bring our plight to the forefront, and we earnestly request your support in ventilating our voice throughout India.

Background Information:

With due respect, we would like to inform you that we are N.I.O.S D.El.Ed Teachers from across the country. According to the RTE-2009, every child has the fundamental right to receive primary education from a trained teacher. To ensure the fundamental rights of children, the Indian government passed a bill in both houses of Parliament with consensus in 2017. Through this, government, government-aided, and private school teachers who were untrained as of the 2010 NCTE notification were given the opportunity to complete the D.El.Ed course through NIOS. Thereafter, the Ministry of Human Resource Development (MHRD) issued a letter to all the Secretaries of States and Union Territories, directing that all teachers in government schools must possess minimum qualifications as mandated under the Right to Education Act, 2009, and a last chance was given to all teachers to acquire the same by March 31, 2019.

In 2017, the Modi government urged us to enroll in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) conducted by N.I.O.S. Approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers, who were already employed in government and private primary schools across the country, enrolled. Subsequently, NCTE issued a recognition order to be published in the Gazette, thereby conducting the D.El.Ed program through the Open and Distance Learning (ODL) mode by NIOS, which reduced the duration of the program from 2 years to 18 months. Education Minister Prakash Javadekar (at that time) and our PM Narendra Damodardas Modi emphasized our enrollment in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) through the National Institute of Open Schooling (NIOS). Normally, the program of the course is 2 years (18 months of theory and 6 months of internship), but our course was completed within 2 sessions (18 months) as we were already employed and did not require an internship. NIOS Board conducted all the exams for this course. It was promoted by Prime Minister Narendra Modi.

Current Situation:

According to the rules, this new plan of NCTE and the Modi government had to be published in the Gazette, but NCTE did not comply. As a result, in 2023, after 7 years, the Honourable Supreme Court announced that our degree is not valid for new recruitment. We cannot apply for any new recruitment in government schools and will not be able to do so in the future due to the negligence of NCTE and the false guarantee by Modi. Due to this mistake by Narendra Modi, today, 14 lakh families are suffering, with no solution in sight.

Our Request:

We, the 14 lakh affected teachers, humbly request your support to highlight our situation on your channel. Your influence and reach can help us gain the attention of the authorities and the public, potentially leading to a resolution of our predicament. We believe that with your help, we can bring our issue to the forefront and seek justice for the countless teachers who have dedicated their lives to educating the children of our country.

Thank you for your time and consideration. We sincerely hope that you will be able to support us in this crucial matter.

Warm regards,

N.I.O.S D.EL.Ed. session 2017-2019

In 2017, the Modi government urged us to enroll in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) conducted by N.I.O.S. Approximately 14 lakh untrained teachers, who were already employed in government and private primary schools across the country, enrolled. Subsequently, NCTE issued a recognition order to be published in the Gazette, thereby conducting the D.El.Ed program through the Open and Distance Learning (ODL) mode by NIOS, which reduced the duration of the program from 2 years to 18 months. Education Minister Prakash Javadekar (at that time) and our PM Narendra Damodardas Modi emphasized our enrollment in the Diploma in Elementary Education (D.El.Ed) through the National Institute of Open Schooling (NIOS). Normally, the program of the course is 2 years (18 months of theory and 6 months of internship), but our course was completed within 2 sessions (18 months) as we were already employed and did not require an internship. We cannot apply for any new recruitment in government schools and will not be able to do so in the future due to the negligence of NCTE and the false guarantee by Modi. Due to this mistake by Narendra Modi, today, 14 lakh families are suffering, with no solution in sight.

Subject: Urgent Appeal for Regular Teacher Recruitment in Gujarat

Respected Sir,

I hope this message finds you well. I am writing to bring to your attention a matter of grave concern regarding the recruitment of regular teachers in Gujarat.

For a long time, we have been demanding the recruitment of regular teachers in Gujarat. Despite numerous requisitions and applications, the Education Minister of Gujarat has not taken any action to list TAT and TET passed candidates. We have been protesting for over a year, yet our voices remain unheard. 

We find ourselves in an unfortunate situation, both in terms of employment and the lack of response from the government. Despite our persistent efforts, the Gujarat government and the Education Minister have shown no willingness to address our demands. Instead of engaging with us constructively, the government has resorted to using police force to suppress our peaceful protests. This authoritarian approach is deeply concerning, especially given that we are educated individuals who understand our democratic rights.

We exercise our right to vote every five years, and it is becoming increasingly clear that we need to reconsider whom we entrust with the leadership of Gujarat. We are committed to securing permanent recruitment for teachers, and we will continue to advocate for our cause until it is achieved.

We urge you to take immediate action to address our demands and ensure the recruitment of qualified teachers in Gujarat. The future of our state's education system depends on it.

Regards,
All Teachers
Gujarat TAT TET Pass Candidate

Subject: Urgent Appeal for Regular Teacher Recruitment in Gujarat

Respected Sir,

I hope this message finds you well. I am writing to bring to your attention a matter of grave concern regarding the recruitment of regular teachers in Gujarat.

For a long time, we have been demanding the recruitment of regular teachers in Gujarat. Despite numerous requisitions and applications, the Education Minister of Gujarat has not taken any action to list TAT and TET passed candidates. We have been protesting for over a year, yet our voices remain unheard. 

We find ourselves in an unfortunate situation, both in terms of employment and the lack of response from the government. Despite our persistent efforts, the Gujarat government and the Education Minister have shown no willingness to address our demands. Instead of engaging with us constructively, the government has resorted to using police force to suppress our peaceful protests. This authoritarian approach is deeply concerning, especially given that we are educated individuals who understand our democratic rights.

We exercise our right to vote every five years, and it is becoming increasingly clear that we need to reconsider whom we entrust with the leadership of Gujarat. We are committed to securing permanent recruitment for teachers, and we will continue to advocate for our cause until it is achieved.

We urge you to take immediate action to address our demands and ensure the recruitment of qualified teachers in Gujarat. The future of our state's education system depends on it.

Regards,
All Teachers
Gujarat TAT TET Pass Candidate

Subject: Urgent Appeal for Regular Teacher Recruitment in Gujarat


Respected Sir,


I hope this message finds you well. I am writing to bring to your attention a matter of grave concern regarding the recruitment of regular teachers in Gujarat.


For a long time, we have been demanding the recruitment of regular teachers in Gujarat. Despite numerous requisitions and applications, the Education Minister of Gujarat has not taken any action to list TAT and TET passed candidates. We have been protesting for over a year, yet our voices remain unheard.Â 


We find ourselves in an unfortunate situation, both in terms of employment and the lack of response from the government. Despite our persistent efforts, the Gujarat government and the Education Minister have shown no willingness to address our demands. Instead of engaging with us constructively, the government has resorted to using police force to suppress our peaceful protests. This authoritarian approach is deeply concerning, especially given that we are educated individuals who understand our democratic rights.


We exercise our right to vote every five years, and it is becoming increasingly clear that we need to reconsider whom we entrust with the leadership of Gujarat. We are committed to securing permanent recruitment for teachers, and we will continue to advocate for our cause until it is achieved.


We urge you to take immediate action to address our demands and ensure the recruitment of qualified teachers in Gujarat. The future of our state's education system depends on it.


Regards,

All Teachers

Gujarat TAT TET Pass CandidateÂ

Respected Dhruv Rathi Ji,
We are candidates for CPLO recruitment of CRID department of Haryana government, please take our grievance to the public through your video.

Haryana government has recently completed the recruitment of CPLO through CRID department. In which all the candidates filled the form for CPLO exam whose fee was Rs 1000 and Pre and Mains 2 high level exams were taken. After passing the exam, when the result of the recruitment came, the candidates were divided into ASK OPERATOR and LCLO (Local Committee Local Operator), in which only Rs 6000 honorarium has been fixed for ASK Operator (CPLO) and for the candidates who have been given offer letter for LCLO post, no fixed salary has been kept, they have been kept on commission basis. Earlier, the work of LCLO was taken from CSC OPERATOR, who were made to work for free for 4 years and no salary or commission was given.

There was no post named LCLO.  Everyone had given the CPLO exam, so everyone should have been made CPLO.

We all candidates are very upset and have appealed to everyone in the Haryana government, from the Chief Minister, former Chief Minister to MLAs, MPs, DCs, ADCs etc. but no one is listening to us.

We all CPLOs, LCLOs have our last hope from you.

Please raise our voice and make a video for us.

We hope for your cooperation.

We are students of your home state Haryana.

All LCLOs and CPLOs are graduates and more educated than that.

It is not possible to survive on a monthly salary of Rs. 6000, nor on commission, which has not been received even a penny till date.

Please make a video for us.

We all 7500 candidates and our families will always be grateful to you.

 We have mainly only 2 demands from the government

1. All of them had filled the form for the job of CPLO and had given the exam of CPLO, therefore all the candidates who have been made LCLO should be appointed on the post of CPLO.

2. Computer operator is a technical post, hence we should be given all the government allowances and salary like Haryana Roadways driver i.e. Rs 25,400 (C group).

Thank you.

Dear Dhruv,

I am a teacher, and I want to extend my love and respect to you. My students benefit greatly from your videos, and I often play them in my classes.

I humbly request you to create a video on the topic of online hotel booking. I have been cheated by online booking websites and hotel management teams multiple times. In fact, this is the fifth time I have ended up paying three times the hotel bill.

Here's my full story: I booked a deluxe room for myself, my wife, and our 6-month-old child. I paid the full amount for a one-day stay online. However, when I arrived at the hotel for check-in, the receptionist informed me that they do not accept online bookings and that I needed to book directly. We were exhausted and carrying our child, so I had no choice but to pay three times the amount I had already paid online.

When I contacted customer care, they claimed that the hotel management had not received any payment from me. I asked for a bill at the hotel when making the additional payment, but they said there was no bill and asked me to send the amount via the PhonePe app.

I provided proof of my payments to the online booking site, but they insisted that they needed an official bill and did not accept PhonePe payments as valid proof. They even accused me of lying. Despite having all the evidence of my payments, including the initial online payment and the PhonePe payment, they refused to help. Additionally, although my booking included a meal, no meal was served.

I have all the evidence to back up my claims if you need them. This has happened to me five times, and each time I witnessed other customers arguing with the hotel staff over similar issues.

This is a significant scam affecting many people who use hotels. Please consider making an educational video on this subject. It is my humble request.

Your follower.
